    <questiontext format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Find the values of \(x\) and \(y\), from the following expressions. Give your answer as a set containing the pairs of points which satisfy the equation, e.g. Â \(\left( \left\{[x_1, y_1],[x_2, y_2] \right\}\right)\): <br /> \[ \left. \begin{array}{rcl} {@cfx2*x^2+cfy2*y^2@} &amp;=&amp;{@k2@} \\ {@cfx*x+cfy*y@} &amp;=&amp;{@k1@} \end{array} \right\} \] <br /> \([x,y] \in \) [[input:ans]] [[validation:ans]]</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>By rearranging the linear equation, \({@cfx*x+cfy*y@} = {@k1@} \) we obtain: \[ y = {@(k1-cfx*x)/cfy@}, \] which we can substitute into the quadratic to give: \[ {@cfx2*x^2+cfy2*((k1-cfx*x)/cfy)^2@} = {@k2@}. \] This can be rearranged into the more familiar quadratic form: \[ {@(cfx2+(cfx^2/cfy^2))*x^2-(2*cfx*k1*x)/cfy^2+k1^2/cfy^2-k2@} = 0. \] Solving this gives \( x = 3\) or \(x = -1 \). By substituting these back into the linear equation you can find the corresponding values of y. ( \(y = -1\) and \(y = 3\) respectively). Therefore, the solution set is: \[ (x,y) \in \left\{ [3,-1] , [-1,3] \right\}. \]</p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
